\section{Manufacturing, Assembling, and the Testing Processes}
\textbf{OE fabrication} : As discussed above, TSMC will play a crucial role in fabricating the PICs, EICs and integrating them and of the CPO system. Their COUPE platform appears to be the solution of choice for next generation CPO endpoints. Global Foundries, and Tower are the foundries who have strong SiPho capabilities, but their lack of leading edge CMOS and advanced packaging constrain their ability to provide the higher bandwidth OEs of the future.

\textbf{Advanced packaging} : Outsourced Semiconductor Assembly and Test (OSAT) providers will focus on the back-end processes: including OE packaging, OE testing, and system packaging (laser and coupler integration \& testing).

ASE/SPIL (3711.TW), Amkor (\$AMKR), and Shunsin (6451.TW) are primary providers of such solutions. Among them, ASE stands out as a key supplier in Nvidia’s supply chain, including involvement in the future Rubin-rack CPO systems, while Shunsin maintains close ties with Broadcom.

Other notable names are Fabrinet (\$FN), TFC Optical (300394.SH), and Foxconn (2354.TW). Fabrinet has long served as the module assembler for Nvidia’s in-house optical module units and is now actively building capabilities in OE packaging, testing, and full system assembly. Fabrinet is also viewed as one of the potential candidates for Broadcom’s CPO system assembly work, alongside Micas and Foxconn.

TFC has been working closely with Nvidia on CPO design for the past 3-4 years and will be a main supplier for FAUs. The company has been investing in advanced packaging facilities in Suzhou, China, signaling its ambition to secure a larger role in the CPO supply chain.

\textbf{Electro-optical (E/O) testing equipment} : During the testing process, the service vendors mentioned above use electro-optical (E/O) testing tools to ensure system reliability. However, the industry is still developing and has yet to fully converge on a standardized testing methodology for photonic engines. Each vendor is developing various solutions to gain a foothold in this emerging space.

Other key equipment providers in the CPO supply chain include Keysight, Ficontec, Teradyne, Advantest, FormFactor, Chroma, Anritsu, and Multilane. Among them, Keysight is a large player in the field - they are known for providing high-speed testing equipment with premium quality (and premium price!). For example, they \href{https://www.keysight.com/us/en/about/newsroom/news-releases/2025/0325-pr25-056-keysights-new-sampling-oscilloscopes-revolutionize-1-6t-transceiver-optical-testing-for-ai-data-centers.html}{recently announced two new oscilloscopes for 1.6T optical transceiver testing} . Due to their position in the market, they can well benefit from the CPO trend.

Ficontec has a strong foundation in photonics testing and is now also actively expanding its electrical testing capabilities. One of its key strengths is wafer-level photonic testing -- which improves the efficiency of the traditionally inefficient photonic testing process. For example, the company \href{https://www.ficontec.com/ficontec-releases-innovative-wafer-level-test-cell-to-complement-existing-ate/}{recently introduced a new high-throughput wafer-level testing tool for PICs} , compatible with existing semi ATE architecture. The machine is claimed as the industry’s first double-sided wafer testing machine. In addition to testing equipment, Ficontec also provides FAU assembly and coupling machines, which we’ll explore in more detail in the next section.

Teradyne is also a large player in the field, with a strong historical presence in electrical testing, but the company has been “very serious” about getting into photonic testing. For example, the company has also recently acquired a startup specializing in packaged optical testing, a move that reflects its strategic push to build out capabilities for CPO.

Chroma has been supplying photonic testing equipment for laser diodes used in 3D sensing and optical communications, and it has the potential to leverage this expertise to enter the CPO space. However, the company’s pace of innovation currently lags some of its competitors.

